{#if lang === 'en'}

[agent-browser](https://github.com/vercel-labs/agent-browser) is a CLI that lets AI agents interact with your browser -- click, type, read elements, take screenshots. Think of it as giving Claude Code hands in the browser.

If you've used Chrome DevTools MCP (30k tokens per call) or the Claude Chrome extension (permission prompts on every click), this is the lightweight alternative. ~100 tokens per snapshot instead of 30,000.

## Install

```bash
npm install -g agent-browser
```

## Connect to Your Browser

Two options:

### Option A: Use Your Existing Chrome

Open `chrome://inspect/#remote-debugging` in Chrome:

<img src={chromeRemoteDebugging} alt="Chrome remote debugging settings with 'Allow remote debugging' enabled" />

Check "Allow remote debugging." Now agent-browser connects to your actual browser with all your login sessions:

```bash
agent-browser --cdp-url ws://127.0.0.1:41175 snapshot -i
```

### Option B: Let agent-browser Launch One

```bash
agent-browser open http://localhost:5173
```

Launches a new browser instance. Simpler, but no existing sessions.

## Install the Skill for Claude Code

The skill teaches Claude Code when and how to use agent-browser. Without it, Claude doesn't know agent-browser exists.

```bash
npx skills install vercel-labs/agent-browser
```

<img src={skillsInstall} alt="Skills installer showing agent-browser skill ready to install" />

Select "agent-browser" and install. Now Claude Code knows the commands.

## What Claude Can Do With It

You don't run these commands -- Claude does. Once the skill is installed, Claude can:

- **Read the page** -- see every button, input, link, and alert as a compact text snapshot (~100 tokens)
- **Click, type, submit** -- interact with forms, buttons, dropdowns
- **Take screenshots** -- capture visual state for layout checks
- **Read console/errors** -- see browser errors without you copy-pasting
- **Run JavaScript** -- evaluate expressions, check state
- **Manage tabs** -- open pages, switch between them

## What It Looks Like

You say: "The checkout form validation isn't working."

Claude opens the page, submits an empty form, sees no error appears, reads the source, fixes the validator, waits for hot-reload, submits again, sees the validation error show up, and reports back: "Fixed. Required field validation was missing on email."

No back-and-forth. No "can you check if it works?" Claude verified its own fix.

